---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
const reviewed = "June 2026";
---
<Base
  title="Company Formation & Tax in Montenegro 2026: d.o.o. & Progressive Tax | ARM Management"
  description="A current guide to setting up a company in Montenegro — the d.o.o., the progressive 9–15% corporate tax, 21% VAT, euro use, and registration via the CRPS, with official sources."
>
  <main>
    <section class="page-hero">
      <div class="page-hero__bg" style="background-image:url('/images/ed-zurich.jpg')"></div>
      <div class="page-hero__overlay"></div>
      <div class="page-hero__content container">
        <span class="eyebrow">Guide · Montenegro</span>
        <h1>Company Formation &amp; Tax in Montenegro</h1>
        <p>A euro-using EU candidate on the Adriatic — the d.o.o., a low progressive corporate tax and €1 minimum capital.</p>
        <div class="btn-row" style="justify-content:flex-start;margin-top:30px">
          <a href="/contact" class="btn-primary">Speak With a Senior Advisor →</a>
          <a href="/services/company-formation" class="btn-secondary">Company Formation Services</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section section--warm">
      <div class="container--narrow">
        <div class="guide-meta reveal">
          <span><strong>Last reviewed:</strong> {reviewed}</span>
          <span><strong>Primary source:</strong>
            <a href="https://www.gov.me/en/uprava-prihoda-i-carina" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Revenue &amp; Customs Administration</a>
          </span>
        </div>

        <div class="prose">
          <p class="reveal lede">Montenegro is the most advanced Western Balkan candidate for EU membership and already uses the euro as its currency, so a Montenegrin company trades in euros without exchange-rate risk. Its corporate tax is progressive but starts low, which suits lean and reinvesting businesses.</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">Choosing an entity</h2>
          <p class="reveal">The standard vehicle is the <strong>d.o.o.</strong> (DOO, private limited company), which can be formed with just <strong>€1</strong> of share capital. Registration is handled by the <strong>CRPS</strong> (Central Registry of Business Entities), typically within roughly seven to ten working days, after which the company registers with the <strong>Revenue and Customs Administration</strong> for tax. Foreign owners and directors face no residency requirement, and the company can be used to support a temporary residence and work permit.</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">Corporate tax and VAT</h2>
          <div class="rate-table reveal">
            <table>
              <thead><tr><th>Tax</th><th>Rate</th></tr></thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>Profit up to €100,000</td><td>9%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Profit €100,000 – €1.5m</td><td>12%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Profit above €1.5m</td><td>15%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>VAT (standard)</td><td>21%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>VAT registration threshold</td><td>€30,000</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p class="reveal">Corporate income tax is <strong>progressive</strong>: 9% on profit up to €100,000, 12% on the slice from €100,000 to €1.5m, and 15% above €1.5m — among the lowest effective rates in Europe for smaller companies. VAT is <strong>21%</strong> standard, with reduced rates of 7% and 15%; registration is mandatory once turnover exceeds <strong>€30,000</strong> in any twelve-month period, and once registered a company cannot deregister for at least three years. Dividends generally carry a 15% withholding tax (with a local surtax that lifts the effective rate slightly), rising to 30% for payments to non-cooperative jurisdictions.</p>

          <div class="callout reveal">
            <strong>Euro stability without eurozone membership.</strong> Using the euro removes conversion friction, and the 9% entry rate is genuinely competitive. But Montenegro is not in the EU single market, the VAT threshold is low (€30,000), and the three-year VAT lock-in is worth planning around from the start.
          </div>

          <h2 class="reveal">Frequently asked questions</h2>
          <div class="reveal">
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>What is the corporate tax rate in Montenegro?</h4><p>Progressive: 9% on profit up to €100,000, 12% from €100,000 to €1.5m, and 15% above €1.5m.</p></div>
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>How much capital do I need for a Montenegrin d.o.o.?</h4><p>€1 minimum share capital.</p></div>
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>What is the Montenegrin VAT rate?</h4><p>21% standard, with reduced rates of 7% and 15%; registration applies above €30,000 turnover.</p></div>
          </div>

          <h2 class="reveal">Official sources</h2>
          <ul class="sources reveal">
            <li><a href="https://www.gov.me/en/uprava-prihoda-i-carina" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Revenue &amp; Customs Administration of Montenegro</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.crps.me/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Central Registry of Business Entities (CRPS)</a></li>
          </ul>

          <p class="reveal disclaimer">This guide is general information prepared by ARM Management and is current as at {reviewed}. It is not legal or tax advice; rules and thresholds change. Confirm against the Revenue &amp; Customs Administration, or with an advisor, before acting.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="cta-section guide-cta">
      <span class="eyebrow is-center reveal" style="justify-content:center">Speak With ARM</span>
      <h2 class="reveal">Set up in Montenegro with confidence.</h2>
      <p class="reveal">ARM Management advises international companies on Montenegrin entity formation, registration and tax compliance, alongside wider Balkan and EU structuring. Begin with a confidential conversation.</p>
      <div class="btn-row reveal">
        <a href="/contact" class="btn-primary">Schedule a Consultation →</a>
        <a href="/services/company-formation" class="btn-secondary">Company Formation Services</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Article","headline":"Company Formation & Tax in Montenegro 2026","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"ARM Management"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"ARM Management"},"dateModified":"2026-06-01","mainEntityOfPage":"https://arm-management.com/insights/montenegro-company-formation"})} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What is the corporate tax rate in Montenegro?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Progressive: 9% on profit up to €100,000, 12% from €100,000 to €1.5m, and 15% above €1.5m."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How much capital do I need for a Montenegrin d.o.o.?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"€1 minimum share capital."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What is the Montenegrin VAT rate?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"21% standard, with reduced rates of 7% and 15%; registration applies above €30,000 turnover."}}]})} />
</Base>
